{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254693/1930040701/0209.xml":{"full_text":"LARGE TAX REDUCTIONS ANNOUNCED FOR FAIRFAX COUNTY\nBUDGET SLASH\nCUTS RATES 5\nTfl 25 CENTS\nAction Taken by Supervisors\nComes In Reply to Protest\nAgainst Ever Mounting Levy\nFAIRFAX, Va., April 7.\u2014Fair\nfax county taxpayers will pay a\nlower tax rate next November as\na result of the action of the board\nof supervisors in cutting all bud\nget items to the minimum. Falls\nChurch district, which heretofore\nhas paid one of the highest rates\nIn the cdunty will get a reduc\ntion of 25 cents, and Le? and\nMt. Vernon districts will pay 5\ncents less.\nReductions were made in re\nsponse to a universal demand for\nrelief from constantly increasing\nburdens. In making the cuts sev\neral items considered essential by\nmany were reduced or eliminated\naltogether.\nThe reduced budget, according\nto Commonwealth Attorney Wil\nson Farr, will prevent employ\nment of an additional ieputy\nsheriff as recently authorised,\neliminate all money for the ex\npenses of a park and planning\ncommission and prevent the\ncounty board of supervisors from\nvoting a salary increase for them\nselves as recently authorized by\nlaw.\nThe rates finally agreed on are\n$2.50 for Providence district, a\ndecrease of 10 cents; s>3s for\nLee and Centerville districts, a\ndecrease of 5 cents; $2.55 for Mt.\nVernon district, a decrease of 5\ncents; $3.20 in Falls Church dis\ntrict, a decrease of 25 cents, 9nd\n$3.50 in Dranesville district, a\ndecrease of 15 cents.\nAll districts will pay 40 cents\nfor the general county levy. 15\ncents for the Confederate pension\nfund: 99 cents for county roads\naside from roads in incorporated\ntowns: 90 cents for schools, and\n1 cent for the district road levy,\na general total of $2.35.\nLIOUDFCHARGE\nNETS YEAR\nCHARLES TOWN, W. Va., April\n7.\u2014John Miller, of Winchester,\nVa., was sentenced in Federal\nCourt here to a year and a day in\nthe Atlanta penitentiary for pos\nsession and transportation of a\nsmall quantity of liquor.\nMiller was arrested several\nmonths ago by State and Federal\nofficers while traveling toward\nMartinsburg, several miles from\nCharles Town.\nGeorgetown Beats\nHarvard in Debate\nUpholding the affirmative on\nthe subject, \u201cResolved, That the\nKellogg peace pact is a sound\nbasis for the foreign policy of\nthe United States,\u201d the George\ntown University debating team\nlast night defeated the team of\nHarvard University.\nThe debate was held in Gaston\nHall, Georgetown University. The\ndecision went to Georgetown by\na vote of four to one. The\nwinning team was composed of\nWilliam A. Sullivan. John C.\nHayes and John F. Lynch.\nStudents Making Own Easter Dresses\nBBBBBBBBBRBM^\u2022\u2022\u2022 >0 8888\n\u25a0BtJMI INMBL.4iBHBBfcs \u25a0\u25a0ch*\n\u00bbO I '\"-31 BBRr W fl\nfl! \"Us is< 9\n.of I\n.Owbfc flfe-\".'-.\nII W C M*' \u00abb& JIHBB' fl\nPi' fIH\nWt t 1 lUm\u00dfse\n'*WL4. I A\nATO\nF Jk;.\\ 1 i\nI\nr UHWrJr rMli i\nil&u-' I\n<d..~ I\n\u2014Tlm-a Staff Photo\nANNETTE FRANCES DOROTHY\nMEMBERS OF THE domestic art class at the Stuart Junior High School, Fourth\nand E Streets Northeast, are making their own Easter dresses. Annette Richardson,\n107 Fifth St. N. E., and Frances Robinson, 203 Third St. N. E., are cutting out\ndresses while Dorothy Harris, 121 C St. N. \u2019E., operates the sewing machine. All are\nin Seventh B-2 grade. i\nSPORTING ENTHUSIASTS FLOCK TO RACES AT MIDDLEBURG, VIRGINIA\n.A s v .v. v z z J A\nBi i a\nWfT' Ha'. JU\nf\nE- S i J..<\njB K I Li \u00abSI\nL. -SIH IF b B\nfwH r<i\u00dfl\nw JMBBWpB B W W* B B JI\nIBfW\u2019W a A I f\nbl I b Ik\nifeSi\nk. h\n*x-\nFASHION REVUE\nON TONIGHT\nThe fashion revue and frolic\nof Capital Forest, No. 104, Tall\nCedars of Lebanon, will open to\nnight at 7:30 o'clocktfct the Be\nlasco Theater, when 20 models\nfrom New York will appear in\ngowns furnished by the Hecht\nCompany and several New York\nstores.\nThere will be four scenes m\nthe fashion show, sport, seaside,\nevening and bridal. In addition\nto the fashion revue, eight head\nline acts from New York shows\nwill be featured. They will in\nclude Jack Kane, Ealine Manzi,\nKish Sonia, the Carrol Sisters,\nEsther Melick and H. Foster\nWelch.\nFollowing the second per\nformance at 9:30 o\u2019clock, the win\nners of awards in the popularity\ncontest will be announced by\nJohn Q. Slye, chairman of the\ncommittee in charge. The win\nner will be awarded a diamond\nring. The second prize will be a\nweek\u2019s trip to Atlantic City, and\nthe third prize a complete travel\ning bag.\nIn addition to Syle.the com\nmittee is comprised of Frank\nBirgfeld, Samuel L. Marks and\nAlvah Patterson.\nFirst Panama Pilot\nDies at Age of 72\nCOLON, April 7 (1.N.5.).\u2014 Capt.\nJohn Constantine, 72, the first\ncanal pilot in the service of the\nUnited States Government, died\nyesterday.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIME#\nGEN. GUY V. HENRY, DAUGHTER AND WIFE\nTEN THOUSAND RACE FANS, including many\nfrom the social register lists, plus ideal weather con\ntributed to a perfect opening of the meets at Middle\nburg, Va., Saturday. Ballast, Second ridden by Noel\nLaing, Amissville, Va., won the Middleburg Hunt Cup,\na 4-mile cross-country race held under the rules of the\nMillionths of an Inch\nMeasured By Gauge\nSome gauge interesting facts\nabout Johansson were related by\nFaye White, of the Ford Motor\nCompany, who, in outlining the\nhistory of that instrument oe\nfore the Northwest section of\nthe Society of Automotive Engi\nneers, said that Carl Johansson,\n\u201cthe father of accuracy.\u201d is rh3\nonly living man who has reduced\nanything definitely to milliastns\nof an inch.\nWhen foreman of the Swedish\ngovernment arsenal, he conceived\nthe idea of measuring by means\nof solid blocks. The difficulty\nof the problem lay in producing,\nin steel, two flat surfaces that\nparallel each other perfectly.\nThe -first set of steel blocks meet\ning these conditions was made in\n1897.\nHaving at last procured the\nright sort of steel, Johansson had\nto produce a finish so fine as to\nConfederate Sons\nGather Tomorrow\nWashington Camp, Sons of\nConfederate Veterans, will meet\ntomorrow night at 8 o\u2019clock at\nthe Confederate Memorial Home,\n1322 Vermont Ave. N. W. Rep\nresentative Charles L. Abernethy,\nof North Carolina, will be the\nprincipal speaker.\nA program of entertainment\nand dancing will follow the busi- I\nness meeting. Mrs. Myra Marks\nwill sing several old-fashioned\nsongs. i\nI HI li 11/C \u25a0Titffljo\nIl Ww 18->7wh BY Wr\nI Ml I Bft Wil 11 n\n1 Er jLBT Isl I B mW BW\nJ iuH! BaAbl I\nK| fls <Bt i\n.Ma\n\nMBMHII A]?lr aWB\u201d\naSjfcfl^^^^f^l' 'a'\nJ\"\ngive a surface resembling quick\nsilver in appearance. Pit to\ngether, two of these surfaces\nwould resist a straight pull of\n210 pounds per square inch at\nright angles to the surfaces.\nWhen a number of blocks thus\nmade are built up together, a\ntwist does not affect vhe mesa\nurement of the complete assem\nbly more than 0.000002 inches\nper block.\nThree types of Johansson\ngauges are now produced, being\nguaranteed to vary, respectively,\nnot over 2, 4 and 8 millionths of\nan inih. They are intended for\nlaboratory inspection and work\ning operation, respectively. There\nis now, in the Ford plant, in De\ntroit, a laboratory set chat is\naccurate to less than 0.000031\ninch, the only set of its accu\nracy in the world, according to\nMr. White.\nRADIO VALUABLE\nIN EDUCATION\nThe use of radio in education,\naccording to the majority of\nAmerican colleges, is an element\nof boundless potenitalities and\nshould be developed to the full\nest extent. This is the report\nof the Interior Department as a\nresult of a nation-wide question\nnaire.\nOut of 23 answers received so\nfar all but two favored the plan\nof radio education. Os these\ntwo, the University of California\nreported that it does not be\nlieve in the importance of the\nradio as an educational factor.\nThe other dissenting institution\nwas the Colorado State Agri\ncultural College, the members of\nwhose faculty \u201care not convinced\nof the value of education by\nradio. Some are actively op\nposed to its use.\u201d\nThe other 21 institutions, how\never, expressed conviction tha:\nthe radio field offers opportunity\nof a vast development in itself\nand would also aid greatly in the\neducation of persons who are\nnow unable to attend classes.\nDr. Dryden Will Speak\nOn \u201cPlane Propellor\u201d\n\u201cThe Airplane Propellor\u201d will\nbe the subject of a lecture by\nDr. Hugh L. Dryden, of the\nBureau of Standards, at a meet\ning of the Standards Flying club\ntomorrow night at 8 o\u2019clock at\nthe Bureau of Standards.\nTAKES PAIN OUT OF\nCORNS Wfjrn\nnpir liquid drops are safe L&jj\nNO excuse for pain- can peel it off. Millions KcU\nfol coms and cak use it. Beware of imita-\nloses. Only one drop turns. Get the neal\u201cG eta- V V\nLi u It \u2014for sale every- tx V R\nof this amazing liquid- wh re _ 1 A\nremoves them scientif- OBT8 IT i ne Chicago.\nically. First, it deadens A\u2014 f\npain in 3 seconds. Then\n\u2022am shrtvala up so yoe BP Wi\nT*A\u00ab National Daily\nWIMMILL\u2019S ENTRY WINNING STEEPLECHASE\nNational Steeplechase and Hunts Association on the\nD. C. Santis property. Princess Clodelly and Happy\nNovelty won the first and second parts respectively of\nthe Loudoun Plate. Jack Skinner and Early Potter,\nriders, were among the first casualties, though their\naccidents were slight and their injuries minor. More\nthan 50 entrants marked the opening and the feature\nAD AAEN TO DINE\nWITH PARRISH\nAmos Parrish, of New York,\nstyle analyst of The Washington\nTimes and business diagnostician,\nwill be the guest speaker of the\nAdvertising Club tomorrow at\n12:15 o\u2019clock in the auditorium\nof the National Press Club. His\ntopic will be \u201cFashion.\u201d\nThe luncheon promise,' to be a\nrecord breaker in the matter of\nattendance as from acceptances\nthus far it is indicated that the j\nauditorium of the Press Club will\nbe filled to capacity.\nIn addition to members of the\nlocal Advertising Club, officers of\nthe Advertising Federation of\nAmerica will be present to hear\nthe style analyst.\nAnswers Questions\nParrish, according to Managing\nDirector Charles J. Columbus,\nexecutive secretary of the local\norganization, has agreed to an\nswer any questions asked by\nthose present. This of course\nwill be limited in view of the\ntime element.\nAmong those who will be pres\nent are. C. C. Younggreen of\nMilwaukee, Wis\u201e president of the\nAdvertising Federation: Walter A.\nStrong, publisher of the Chicago\nDaily News; Gilbert T. Hodges of\nthe New York Sun and Earl\nPearson of ,New York, general\nmanager of the Federation.\nWill Aid Merchants\nThe visit of the style expert is\nhefaided as a most fortuitous\ncircumstance by Columbus who\nsaid that in view of the business\noutlook the visit will be of con\nsiderable importance to Washing\nton merchants.\nImmediately following the lun\ncheon meeting of the club, at\nwhich Ernest Johnson will preside\nofficers of the federation and the\nlocal club will meet for the\npurpose of drafting final plans\nfor the convention to be held\nhere next month.\n|CREERON\n614 Twelfth Street\nFor Home Milliners\nEASTER Trimmings\nand Novelties\n39c, 75c to\nNew Arrival of Ostrich and\nFancy Feathers, Flowers,\nWreaths and Ornaments\ny Largest Variety in the City\nTo Select From\nMONDAY, APRIL 7, 1030\nFive Census Workers\nResign But Others\nSeize Pencils\nFive of the crew of census\nenumerators at work in the\nDistrict have returned their cre\ndentials to Census officials on\nthe ground that they were un-\nable to earn enough to justify\ntheir continuing the work, it\nwas learned today from the\noffice of J. Sterling Moran,\nsupervisor of the census for the\nDistrict.\nMoran stated that the resign\ning enumerators have been re\nplaced and that the change\nwill in no way affect the taking\nof the census in the District.\nRAID NETS STILL\nAND 2 ARRESTS\nSTAUNTON, Va\u201e April 7.\u2014\n\"Caught red-handed\u201d was the\nterm used to describe the cap\nture yesterday of C. W. Parr and\nEldridge Brown, both of nearby\nCrimora, on charges of violating\nthe prohibition law.\nOfficers acting on a tip caught\nthe two men coming from a still\nladen with mash. Whisky mak\ning equipment was taken along\nwith 300 gallons of mash, several\ngallons of spirits, barrels and\nkegs, and a 150 gallon capacity\nstill.\nThe men were bonded before\nMagistrate C. A. Lightner in the\nsum of SSOO for their appearance\nbefore the next term of the\ngrand jury.\nCouldn\u2019t Eat or\nSleep\u2014Gas, GAS\nAll the Time!\nvfc VI\n\u25a0HIHIMHK.-.. wH\u00dfk..i\n\u201cThe gas on my stomach was\nso bad I couldn\u2019t eat or sleep.\nEven my heart hurt. A lady sug\ngested Adlerika. The first dose\nI took brought me relief. Now\nI eat as I wish, sleep fine, and\nnever felt better.\u201d\u2014 Mrt. Jamet\nFiller.\nThe simple glycerin, buckthorn\nbark, saline compound (known\nas Adlerika), acts on BOTH upper\nand loWer bowel. It brings out\nfoul matter you would never be\nlieve was in your system. This\nold matter may have poisoned\nyou for months and caused GAS,\nsour stomach, headache or nervous\nness. i\nTry thia single proof: Take any\n\u00bboHi\ni|MM|| t j Ln\nMi I K'\nI jr \u25a0w w i\ngj I\" /I B\nm flHn 1\n'ff iff *Mi Mi m\niff fly M st Iff i J\nIff g I\nIF f\nI Jr i <.,J\nU.J JJ.III 111 I '('II I r I r MMHMB\n\u2014AI! International Photo\u00ae\nMRS. DUNCAN CAMERON AND DAUGHTERS\nriding of the day was contributed by Bobby Young,\nNew York. Among the Washingtonians on the scene\nwere Gen. Guy V. Henry, new chief of cavalry, suc\nceeding Herbert B. Crosby, new District Commissioner;\nhe was accompanied by Mrs. Henry and daughter,\nMary. Also Mrs. Cameron, Washington and Newport,\nwith daughters Elsie and Phoebe Quimby.\nFISHBURN SEEN\nEASY VICTOR\nB